# HexCurse — Taskmaster + local LM Studio (OpenAI-compatible API)
# LM Studio: OpenAI-compatible Local Server (this workspace: Tailscale/LAN host below). Load qwen3.5-2b (~8k context) or match modelId in .taskmaster/config.json.

OPENAI_API_KEY="lm-studio"
OPENAI_BASE_URL="http://100.80.17.40:1234/v1"

# If no OpenAI-compatible server is reachable, `task-master parse-prd` and `setup.js --run-hexcurse` cannot call an LLM. In that case, rebuild `.taskmaster/tasks/tasks.json` from `NORTH_STAR.md` + `.taskmaster/docs/prd.txt` with the same scope parse-prd would cover (Cursor agent or human). See `docs/directives/D-HEXCURSE-PRODUCT-STACK-005.md` Part B.

# Optional: installer/Taskmaster context caps (default 8000 when unset for LM Studio installs)
# HEXCURSE_LM_STUDIO_MAX_CONTEXT=8000
# HEXCURSE_LM_STUDIO_BASE_URL=http://100.80.17.40:1234

# Optional: before `task-master parse-prd` during `node cursor-governance/setup.js --run-hexcurse*`, require Cursor CLI login (`agent status` after `agent login`). Does not replace Taskmaster's LLM endpoint (OPENAI_* above); it gates the bridge to match headless workflows. See https://cursor.com/docs/cli/reference/authentication.md and https://cursor.com/docs/cli/headless
# HEXCURSE_PREFLIGHT_CURSOR_AGENT=1

# Optional cloud providers (not used for HexCurse Taskmaster defaults)
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="..."
# PERPLEXITY_API_KEY="..."
# GOOGLE_API_KEY="..."
# MISTRAL_API_KEY="..."
# XAI_API_KEY="..."
# GROQ_API_KEY="..."
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY="..."
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY="..."
# OLLAMA_API_KEY="..."
# GITHUB_API_KEY="..."
#
# Optional: Swarm Protocol MCP (see cursor-governance/bin/swarm-protocol-mcp.js) — any Postgres URL.
# Prefer storing the URI (includes password) in ~/.cursor/swarm-database.env as DATABASE_URL="..." so ~/.cursor/mcp.json stays free of secrets.
# Alternative: Windows User environment variable DATABASE_URL or SWARM_DATABASE_URL (Cursor inherits user env for MCP).
# Avoid pasting the full URI into mcp.json if you sync or share that file.
# Supabase: Dashboard → Project Settings → Database → Connection string (URI).
# Pooler host is often `aws-0-<region>.pooler.supabase.com` or `aws-1-<region>.pooler.supabase.com`; user is `postgres.<project_ref>` (not plain `postgres`).
# Port: dashboard may show pooler on 5432 or 6543 depending on connection mode — use the exact URI Supabase gives you.
# SWARM_DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.[PROJECT_REF]:[YOUR_PASSWORD]@aws-1-[REGION].pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres"
# Local dev fallback:
# SWARM_DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:postgres@127.0.0.1:5432/swarm_protocol"
#
# Optional: Semgrep MCP — if `semgrep` is not on PATH for Cursor, set full path to semgrep.exe (Windows pip --user: %APPDATA%\Python\Python311\Scripts\semgrep.exe).
# Re-merge MCP after setting: `npm run doctor` from repo root (or paste SEMGREP_PATH into ~/.cursor/mcp.json → semgrep.env).
# SEMGREP_PATH=C:\Users\YOU\AppData\Roaming\Python\Python311\Scripts\semgrep.exe
# SEMGREP_APP_TOKEN=   # Semgrep Cloud / Pro (optional)
#
# Optional: node-gyp (Pampa / native npm) on Windows — prefer user env over .npmrc (npm may warn on unknown msvs_version):
# GYP_MSVS_VERSION=2022
# If using 2022, install a Windows 11/10 SDK on that VS instance (VS Installer → Individual components), or node-gyp reports "missing any Windows SDK".